
This bare-metal RTOS achieves multitasking on the STM32F411RET6 by executing direct hardware manipulation, removing the reliance on external libraries.
It shifts between tasks using a Round-Robin scheduler triggered by the ARM Cortex-M4's internal SysTick timer, which is configured to issue an interrupt every 1 millisecond.

Multitasking relies entirely on manipulating the Process Stack Pointer (PSP) and utilizing the PendSV (Pendable Service Call) exception to perform the actual context switch.
When the SysTick interrupt fires, it switches the active task index and pends the PendSV exception, which executes at the lowest priority to guarantee system stability.

Inside the naked assembly function PendSV_Handler, the context switch takes place in two discrete phases:

Saving Context: The state of the currently executing task is preserved. The hardware automatically saves registers R0–R3, R12, LR, PC, and xPSR onto its stack. 
The assembly code then manually pushes the remaining registers (R4–R11) and stores the updated stack pointer into that task's Task Control Block (TCB).

Loading Context: The incoming task's TCB is read to find its saved stack pointer. The assembly engine manually restores registers R4–R11,
loads the new address into the CPU's PSP register, and branches to the special execution return code 0xFFFFFFFD.

This return value forces the ARM core to automatically pop the remaining registers off the new task's stack. 
The CPU reads the task's entry point from the restored Program Counter (PC), smoothly resuming execution of the next application loop.
